<AbstractNarration>Phenomena involving positrons (i.e., the antiparticles of electrons) are&lt;br/&gt;important in many fields including astrophysics, plasma and atomic physics, and materials&lt;br/&gt;science. Much progress has been made recently in these areas through laboratory experiments&lt;br/&gt;that exploit nonneutral plasma techniques. This proposal describes a program of research to&lt;br/&gt;create and understand the physics of novel states of single-component positron plasmas in new&lt;br/&gt;regions of parameter space. These antimatter plasmas will be used, in turn, for a range of&lt;br/&gt;scientific and technological applications.&lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
